g.text: T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding is an unsupervised, and randomized algorithm
only used for data visualization
t-SNE
Algorithm
Key steps
It applies a non-linear dimensionality reduction which focuses
on keeping the highly similar data points close together
in a lower dimensional space
It preserves the local structure of the data using the
student t-distribution to compute the similarity between
two points in a lower dimensional space
The choice of the student distribution rather than a Gaussian
is because it helps to address the crowding and optimization
problem
Convert the high-dimensional Euclidean distance between datapoints
xi and xj into conditional probabilities P(j | i)
Step 1 - Find the pairwise similarities
variance of under
a Gaussian
centered point
This is proportional to their similarity! Nearby points will have
a higher conditional probability, and points that are far away
will have a lower conditional probability
The conditional probability are symmetrized by averaging the two
probabilities
Step 2 - Map each point in a lower dimensional space
This is based on the similarity on the higherdimensional space
yi and yj are the low
dimensional counterparts
of xi and xy
Step 3 - Find a lower dimensional space that minimizes the
mismatch between P(ij) and Q(ij) using GD based on KL-Divergence
Minimizing the KL divergence
means to make Q(i | j)
identical to P(i | j), so
that their representations
in different dimensional
spaces will be similar
Step 4 - Use student t-distribution to compute the similarity
in the low-dimensional space
t-SNE uses a heavy-tailored student t-distribution with one
degree of freedom to compute the similarity between two
points in the low-dimensional space
This creates the probability distribution of points in lower
dimensional space, and reduces the "crowding issue"
Details
t-SNE leverage close point to compute the conditional
probabilities. How many points do we have to consider?
- perplexity: this is the hyperparameter used for selecting the
number of neighbors. Obviously, it highly
depends on the number of data points that
have. In general, it should be in the range 5-50
- n_components: this is the hyperparameter used for selecting
the new dimension, and it is typically 2 or 3
(remember that t-SNE is used for data viz)
